113 academically underprepared students, adult learners, and other
114 categories of higher-need students as identified pursuant to
115 §16-5B-5.
116 (16) LOW-INCOME STUDENT. A student who received a full
117 or partial federal Pell Grant award at any point in the
118 academic year.
119 (17) PERFORMANCE YEAR. The year established by the
120 Outcomes-Based Higher Education Funding Coordinating Committee
121 in discussion with the individual institutions to reflect the
122 most recently completed scholastic year used to measure
123 performance and outcome changes from the established base
124 year.
125 (18) PREMIER RESEARCH UNIVERSITY. A public university
126 whose annual external grants and contracts revenues exceed
127 $100,000,000 based on publicly available audited financial
128 statements.
129 (19) SOME COLLEGE, NO DEGREE. Adults with some
130 postsecondary education, but have not earned a degree or
131 credential, including those who dropped out, are currently
132 enrolled, or took a few classes.
133 (20) STUDENT POSTGRADUATION SUCCESS. A student that is
134 enrolled, employed, or enlisted, as defined in this section,
135 within a time frame of graduating from or completing an
136 educational program established by the Outcomes-Based Higher
137 Education Funding Coordinating Committee in discussion with
138 the individual institutions.
139 (21) STUDENT RETENTION. Keeping students enrolled and
140 engaged in an eligible institution from one academic period to
